With this KIPI module, you can import and convert your files stored in RAW format in one of three formats JPEG, TIFF or PPM.
The conversion is based on the command-line tool dcraw by Dave Coffin. a original quote from Him is: expect from dcraw not that it creates the same results as the software from your camera manufacturers. sometimes you get more dcraw better results!.
First, choose the RAW file to be converted and start the module. the Raw-Image Converter window will then appear in mode for a single image. with the button preview you can view the effect of your current settings to the image.
You can now adjust the values to optimize the conversion process. the first option decides whether the camera settings should be adjusted for white periods. the key parameters such as gamma, brightness and red / blue amplifier can be adjusted. if the result is not optimal, you can process the picture later.
A four-colour RGBG conversion can be selected, so that you can use the contrast information. if your camera works in RGB mode the RGBG switch has no effect.
Once you are happy with the preview, you can choose one of the three output formats and save the conversion results. the filename remains the same, and only the extension is adapted accordingly. JPEG uses a loss-loss algorithm and manufactures for the smallest file sizes.
The tagged image format, TIFF, keeps all the information of your image and uses the lossless LZW compression.
In case you want to edit your images frequently or later, you should not choose the JPEG format, as there is only a limited number of operations allowed before the image quality deteriorates. TIFF and PPM are better adapted to keep the original data.
If you choose JPEG as a storage format, the metadata is stored in the RAW file, stored in the JPEG file in the Exif information.
If you have adapted your settings, you can start with the exit knob. if you want to cancel this process again, you can use abort.
